== Etymology ==
Old English ''feower'', from Germanic ''*fiþworiz'', from PIE ''*kwetwores''. Cognate to German ''vier'', French ''quatre'', Greek ''τεσσαρες'', Russian ''четыре''.

== Number ==
# [[One]] plus [[three]]; [[two]] plus two; two times two.  Represented in Roman numerals as IV and in Arabic numerals as 4. The typical number of [[finger]]s, other than the [[thumb]], on one [[hand]]. Ordinal: [[fourth]].

